Renders typed shorthand entries into a Plover-format dictionary using the "plain" cursor profile — the naive editor model where every closing delimiter is typed literally and the cursor is walked back from the end of the document via movement commands, as opposed to smarter profiles that might rely on editor-native features. Thin file: it's just the plain-profile instantiation of the generic rendering pipeline defined in `render/mod.rs`.

`render_plain(entry: &TypedEntry) -> Result<(String, String), RenderError>` converts a single typed entry to a `(key, value)` Plover dictionary pair by expanding it with the `PLAIN` editor profile (from `crate::editor`) via `entry_events`, then packing the result with `wrap`. `build_plain_dict(entries: &[TypedEntry]) -> Result<BuildResult, RenderError>` runs this over a whole entry set using the shared `build_dict` helper, which also detects and flags stroke collisions (per `BuildResult`'s shape, defined in `render/mod.rs`).

All actual logic — event generation, wrapping into Plover's format, collision detection — lives in `super` (`render/mod.rs`); this file only supplies the `PLAIN` editor constant and fails the same way `render/mod.rs`'s helpers fail (unresolved template chunk or movement-compilation error, both surfaced as `RenderError`). Coupled to `crate::editor::PLAIN` for the actual key-sequence semantics of "plain" editing — changes to what PLAIN means there change output here silently.